#lang racket
;;; The exercise didn't explicitly mention that the reader would need to add the
;;; polar and rectangular packages to the system. I initially thought the complex
;;; package accounted for both somehow. The reader will also need to create an
;;; internal procedure for magnitude, and the other selectors, inside of the
;;; complex package.


;;; Alyssa P. Hacker's recommendation works because once the polar package has
;;; placed an entry in the data-directed table for '(complex) type numbers and
;;; we've defined an outer-level generic procedure for magnitude, we
;;; can look up how to deal with the complex type from the complex-package's
;;; internal procedure. Assuming the internal magnitude procedure of the complex
;;; package is a generic procedure, we'll be directed to one or the other of
;;; the rectangular or polar packages where the actual contents will be dealt
;;; with accordingly to generate the magnitude.


;;; So, to put it plainly, apply-generic is invoked twice. Once when called from
;;; the generic procedure magnitude defined outside of all packages, and once when
;;; called from the internal procedure magnitude, within install-complex-package,
;;; where it is then dispatched to the magnitude procedure within install-rectangular-package.
;;; Phew!

;;; misc =======================================================================
(define (attach-tag type-tag contents)
  (cons type-tag contents))

(define (type-tag datum)
  (if (pair? datum)
      (car datum)
      (error "Bad tagged datum -- TYPE-TAG" datum)))

(define (contents datum)
  (if (pair? datum)
      (cdr datum)
      (error "Bad tagged datum -- CONTENTS" datum)))

(define (apply-generic op . args)
  (let ((type-tags (map type-tag args)))
    (let ((proc (get op type-tags)))
      (if proc
          (apply proc (map contents args))
          (error
           "No method for these types -- APPLY-GENERIC"
           (list op type-tags))))))

;;; Thank you to github user skanev for his upload of exercises!
